##Traveling with the virus: My 28 days on the diamond princess

Wechat media-fox

Features, for those who insist on serious reading options. Sohu News Extreme Day studio.

On March 1, Captain Gennaro Alma became the last person to step off the diamond princess. Photo courtesy of the respondents

ABSTRACT: The luxury cruise ship "Diamond Princess" is like a five-star hotel on the sea. On February 1st more people were diagnosed with COVID-19 pneumonia, as a passenger in Hong Kong was diagnosed. The ship, which carried 3,711 crew members and passengers, once had the second highest number of confirmed cases in the world, more than any other country except China, and was dubbed a "maritime prison" by the media. Without any mental preparation, the captain led the passengers into an unexpected isolation.

As of March 15, the 145 people who had finally disembarked from the cruise ship had completed their health observation and tested negative for the virus. They were allowed to return home from March 16. A total of 712 people on the cruise ship were confirmed to have contracted new crown pneumonia. US Passenger Sarah Arana tells the story of her isolation aboard the Diamond Princess and her return to the US Air Force Base.

By Chen Teng

Editor | Peng Lin

On a deserted California beach on March 6, Sarah watched as the sea she had known since childhood came and went, inhaling and inhaling. She took a deep breath at the thought of a new coronavirus-infected Princess Royal Floating in the open sea. Sarah had just returned from her sister ship, the Diamond Princess of the same brand, which was carrying 3,711 lives, 712 confirmed cases of new pneumonia, seven deaths, and filled with viruses and horror fantasies, on a luxury cruise that almost landed in hell.

To others, the diamond princess was a cold, beautiful ship, too sick to go ashore. But for Sarah, that's where she managed to live out four movies in just 13 days: from Groundhog Day, which repeats itself day in and day out, to The Truman Show, which despairs at not being able to escape her manipulative fate, then there's the The Twilight Zone, which suddenly plunges into a surreal thriller, and then the Hunger Games, which I don't know when it will be selected, culled, and killed.

Now, with the sound of the sea and the sound of birds, Sarah tried to soothe the wounds of his bad luck. The tide rises, the tide falls, and the sea, with its calmness from day to day, teaches her to keep calm and breathe through the ups and downs of life. In a tragedy that could have torn her in half, the 53-year-old unexpectedly found herself stronger than she thought. Disaster is as big as Mount Tai before the collapse, but wrapped in a small body of the soft heart, always take something with it.

Harana/valle de Arana is a social worker with 18 years of experience in crisis intervention. Photo courtesy of the respondents

The following is based on Sarah Arana's account:

The luxury tour

I travel around the world alone a lot, so this is no exception. My friend told me that there will be a lot of celebration activities during the Chinese New Year, so I chose this time to travel. The diamond princess will be in Hong Kong on the first day of the first lunar month. So I paid $2,100 for the January 20th-february 4th Cruise.

The diamond princess departed from Yokohama, Japan, passed through Kagoshima, and arrived in Hong Kong on January 25. But I was really disappointed when Hong Kong cancelled all the rallies, fireworks and other celebrations. I didn't make it, but I tried to look forward to the rest of the trip.

Then we went to Vietnam, kayaked, visited the World Trade Center in Taiwan, ate dumplings, and drank Asian beer at an award winning restaurant. I had a good time. Life on the ship is wonderful, the diamond princess is a beautiful ship, I go to the movies every night in front of the big screen, go to the big theaters to see the best shows, and the casinos, the lobsters, the escargots and the caviar, the crew's service was excellent. It was all very high class. It was my first time on a cruise, and the most extravagant thing I had ever done in most of my life.

This wonderful journey, the last two days, suddenly became very strange. Just as we were about to return to Yokohama, a passenger who had disembarked in Hong Kong was diagnosed with new crown pneumonia, which caused the Japanese government to deny us access to Port of Yokohama, and the diamond princess was temporarily grounded offshore.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Quarantined Diamond Princess. Image courtesy of the Internet

At 6:30 a.m. on Feb. 4, Captain Alma, from Italy, officially declared a 14 day mandatory quarantine, with all passengers confined to their cabins. At first I was just a little worried, not scared. It wasn't until I saw Japanese officials arriving on the ship to take everyone's temperature that I suddenly realized something was wrong.

Everyone was in shock, and almost no one believed what was happening. The passengers immediately formed a facebook group and began working together to get information about the outbreak. The cruise ship has one side facing the sea and the other towards the land. Landward passengers count the number of ambulances parked outside each day to see how many confirmed cases will be taken away that day. They then share this information with the group to let passengers facing the sea know.

Rescue vehicles can be seen from Sarah's room on Feb. 11. Photo courtesy of the respondents

Singing, dancing, face masks

The hardest part of isolation is being stuck in the cabin for long periods of time, with very little activity. Some cabins do not even have windows, passengers will not breathe fresh air for a long time. They had to take turns to go on deck at regular times to get some air, as per the ship's rules. My Room has a balcony, so I can stand out and breathe in the fresh air.

But back in the cabin, I saw the whole world on TV talking about this new, deadly virus, and the number of confirmed cases was increasing rapidly. It was my first time on a cruise ship, my first trip to Japan, and I was even less familiar with the Japanese government, all of these unknowns crammed into this cramped cabin. I was suddenly completely out of my control. I was helpless and desperate. But right now, I decided: how to deal with it, it was the only thing I could control.

It's a coping skill and mindset. Over the course of 18 years, I managed an emergency medical station on burning man and gained experience in crisis intervention. They have prepared me well for this sudden disaster. (editor's Note: Burning Man is an annual anti-traditional Carnival in the black rock desert of the United States.)

The first day of isolation, in order to kill boredom, I dance on the balcony, head is constantly thundering helicopter. If you see anyone dancing in a picture of a cruise ship, it's probably me. I hope my neighbors won't mind my endless loop of American country, Pop, and rock music.

Sarah's room on the diamond princess

By the third day, 41 new cases had been confirmed. We started taking our temperature several times a day. If we have a fever, we have to call the front desk right away, and they'll get us off the ship. That day, I found it a little hard on my own. I decided to send a message to the women traveling alone group, see if anyone else was on the boat, get some support.

No.

But in just a few hours, more than 2,000 women from all over the world came forward and gave me a lot of support and encouragement. That day, Captain Alma was on the radio, officially mentioning our facebook "passenger base. " . He encouraged us to support, help and communicate with each other in the group. All right, let's do it! Under his guidance, we picked up our cabin phones, called other strangers, and placated each other. One of the people I talked to a lot was a family with a 6 year old in a cabin with no fresh air. And a wife whose husband was diagnosed and left on a boat. There were others, of course, and we became friends. We tell each other jokes, laugh as much as we can, and try to do our best. We also talk to people who have been diagnosed and know that they are well taken care of, and many have only mild symptoms and recover quickly.

At the same time, I kept saying to myself, "don't be afraid. I'm not afraid. ". I busied myself researching herbs, drinking tea, chatting online with friends, breathing fresh air on the balcony, basking in the sun, and applying face masks. I try to focus on staying positive, instead of being consumed by fear, keeping my thoughts from the dark corners.

Shipwreck nightmare

However, by day 4-6, as the number of confirmed cases rose rapidly, people began to become frustrated and angry.

You have no idea what will happen tomorrow. Can everyone finally get off the ship? We even wonder how many beds are available in Japan. I heard that two of the patients who were taken to the hospital were sent away six hours later because all the beds in Tokyo and Yokohama were full. But we have over 3,700 people on board. And we're all thinking, "Oh, my God, what if the test comes back positive? "? What's more, no one knows how the virus spreads. People think it's through a vent, or, if someone opens the door, the virus spreads down the hallway.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On Feb. 6, Sarah sneaked open the door and looked down the hall. The cruise staff did not allow passengers to leave the cabin door. Photo courtesy of the respondents

I cried several times, alone in the cabin, with no one to talk to. At the time, people wondered if everyone who got sick would eventually die. We're seeing more and more deaths and more diagnoses on TV in China, and you're on a boat with a virus and more and more people being diagnosed. One night, when the cruise ship was taking us out to get water and poop, the sky was filled with lightning and thunder. I really wondered if I was going to die, too.

I've been having nightmares. In the dream, the Diamond Princess sailed out to sea and was deliberately sunk to the bottom of the sea. I never left Japan and did not go back to my family.

One day, I suddenly smelled a strong chemical taste coming out of the vent, and then my eyes and throat were sore for several seconds, i asked myself, "are they trying to poison us? Are they afraid that everyone on board will get the virus, and they don't want it to spread again, so they're going to kill us all and then sail out into the sea and let it sink? "

This isn't a dream. This is what happens when I'm awake.

The whole process is very intense, but it is very difficult to accurately convey to outsiders, it comes and goes like waves, very strong, terrible. Many passengers are struggling and suffering, some passengers refused to eat, because of fear of food viruses; Some passengers said their blood pressure medicine no chest pain, some Parkinson's medicine no longer, some because of kidney pain crying, some smokers have nowhere to smoke, some next door passengers were diagnosed with their heart also panic... they suffered a lot of psychological trauma, some people get PTSD, and they need therapy.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
During the quarantine, Sarah leaned on the balcony to breathe fresh air to relieve the pressure. Photo courtesy of the respondents

Unite and face this day

In the midst of these traumas, horrible nightmares, fantasies, truths and lies, the captain of the Alma would turn the ship's sides to the sea so that passengers could take turns to see the sea, rather than the rows of ambulances on land. He often speaks to us over the radio every day with warm words, such as "I know this is hard for everyone, I'm sorry, we are with you" , "100% of the air is clean, the virus doesn't travel through air vents, " or "we'll try to do the best we can, " or "my gladiators, let's unite and face the day. ". These words are like a daily lifeline to us.

To relieve our stress, he showed us a lot of new movies, gave us puzzles, games, Japanese Origami, thermos, instant noodles and so on. The father of a six year old with whom I had been supporting told me that they had received toys, Legos, candy, and ice cream from the ship. The children were so happy that when it was finally their turn to get some air on deck, they did not want to go out.

Back then, Captain Alma was also quarantined, but he was still working. The diamond princess was his ship, and he had to deal with the Japanese government, the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare, the crew, embassies, and more than 2,600 frightened, weeping, angry passengers on board, and their endless questions. But he never lost his temper and was never rude to anyone. All the time on the ship, he had the decency and respect to do everything and everyone with great grace.

Under his leadership, the more than 1,000 crew members performed remarkably well under high pressure. In those days when we faced quarantine, viruses and death as much as the crew, I sometimes just wanted to lie down and stand on my head to help me relax, but the crew had to keep working, cabin to cabin.

Like the supply of Three Meals a Day. With passengers on the 15th floor, it's actually very, very difficult to deliver to so many people.

By the Ninth Day of quarantine, I was almost out of tea in my cabin. No tea is a crisis for me personally. I asked the crew if I could have some tea from the Galley. Then the sailor knocked on my door and said, "I didn't know what you liked, so I brought all kinds. ". I'm so happy.

Sarah's tea is given by the crew

Also on that difficult ninth day, I received support from as many as 5,000 women from all over the world in the women traveling alone group! WHOA! I'm so touched.

Every minute, all this support makes a big difference to the feeling of isolation. As intense as the emotions come and go, like a roller coaster, I try to focus on the love I feel, like there's a very friendly Japanese media boat that beats out signs of hope and encouragement every day. And then one day, 35 doctors and 45 nurses came aboard to help us, all of them volunteers, and they just exposed themselves to danger. I have nothing but respect for their compassion and willingness to serve.

I let that love inspire me to keep going. I told myself that it would be a long process, but that it would come to an end.

A Japanese media boat with daily inspirational slogans. Photo courtesy of the respondents

2:00 a.m. , "welcome home. "

Still, the last few days of the quarantine, the whole ship was depressed. More and more people are calling their embassies -- as if the United States, Canada, Australia, the United Kingdom -- to voice our need to evacuate, because we can't stay on the ship anymore. I think quarantine on a ship is a very bad decision. Although there are a lot of people on board, and I know this is going to be difficult, I still think we need to get off this ship and quarantine somewhere else.

The crew brought me the local paper, and the diamond princess was on the front page. This isn't real for me on the boat. Although the picture of the ship looks familiar, it is surrounded by so much fog, darkness and mystery.

By the end of the quarantine, the State Department had finally confirmed that evacuees were coming. But if we get back to the U.S. , we'll need to be quarantined for another 14 days to prevent the virus from spreading. Some passengers were dismayed to hear that there was a 14-day quarantine period after their return to the United States. But I understand the decision, and if it saves a life, then 14 days is worth it. It's my duty as a citizen.

I'm finally going home. I can't stop crying.

The diamond princess made the front page of the media

On Valentine's Day, February 14th, the crew sent roses and chocolates to all the passengers. Captain Alma read a Bible Verse: "Love Bears All things, believes all things, hopes all things, endures all things. Love never fails. I wish you all a happy Valentine's Day. " That night, I was filled with mixed feelings. I was relieved but also a little sad to be leaving the ship soon. It's hard to explain. Just like before I left, the crew sent me another gift, an anchor cross-stitch, hand-embroidered can be used as a necklace to hang up, I like it.

The evacuation took place in the middle of the night on February 16, and everything took longer than expected.

The evacuation was chaotic. We sat on seven buses and watched two empty planes parked in the distance, but we sat there for five hours waiting to board. At night, it's hard to see what's going on around you, much less know what's going on.

But now I know. Because when our plane landed in California, I turned on my phone, and I saw the news, and I knew it was because of the evacuation, and Japanese officials showed up, and they said the test results were in, and 14 of the evacuees were confirmed. The State Department insisted on bringing home the people who were diagnosed, and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention refused, and they argued. But in the end, apparently, the State Department won.

But no one told us there was a confirmed case on the plane. And we didn't see any of the arguments. In several of the embassy's evacuation emails to us, they repeatedly stressed that they would not bring back people with confirmed cases or symptoms, so we decided to take the evacuation plane. I didn't know the confirmed patient was sitting behind the plastic curtain on the plane. I didn't even know anyone was there. That's a 10-hour flight, which means we're exposed to the virus in both the car and the plane.

So when the plane came down and the cell phone said there was a confirmed case on board, a lot of people were very angry. My first reaction was that they were American citizens, that it was right to bring them home, that they should be with their families, that they should be treated on their own soil. I'm a firm believer.

It didn't go well, but when we landed, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, the Department of Health and Human Services, Global Immigration and Quarantine, and various military personnel were lined up at the gate to greet us, the sign said "welcome home, " and everyone was very warm and welcoming. Although we are very tired, but very touched. I've heard the phrase "welcome home" before, but this time it's different. This time it's genuine. I can feel it in my bones. I'll never forget this. It was 2:00 a.m.

On Feb. 15, before being evacuated, the crew presented Sarah with a cross stitch. Photo courtesy of the respondents

A gift from a stranger

Life at Travis was much better, though we were still under strict quarantine. We can go out for a walk, but we have to keep our distance from each other. No one can touch us. This is very different from the quarantine on the ship. We were always on the water, we could feel the water flowing, and the cabin was very small. Now we are back in our own country, there is no language barrier, and on the ground, there is more space, and can go out for a walk, exercise, the overall better.

A lot of people might find that relaxing. Not really, because the constant knocking at the door, delivering food, taking your temperature, sending a message, or asking a question, is not relaxing.

February 20th is my birthday. It's a very difficult day. I was supposed to be with my family, but because of the quarantine, all these parties have been canceled. I turned everything off and sat by myself in complete silence. After a while, there was a knock at the door. I didn't answer it. After a long time, there was another knock at the door. It's the health department. They take my temperature twice a day.

One of them told me to come out. They never asked me out. MY HEART IS SINKING! I knew I was going to be taken away, in a "free" car, to some shiny lab. I almost started to cry.

When I walked out of the room, they started singing happy birthday to me. There was this guy with a guitar, and it sounded like he was rehearsing. Oh, my God. These uniformed health department workers are singing happy birthday to me? They gave me video games and cupcakes. And then he left. After a while, there was another knock at the door. He told me to leave the door open. Then he unloaded piles and piles of express gifts into my room. Some of them are from people who read my facebook plague diary and sent me support.

I can't tell you how much this experience has touched me, and I thank them for their kindness, generosity and love. Thank you.

Staff members singing happy birthday to Sarah

On March 1, the last day of the quarantine, we received a farewell video from Captain Alma. I was strangely comforted by the familiar voice of the captain of the Diamond Princess.

The captain was the last person to step off the diamond princess, and when I saw the picture of him leaving, I was devastated. By now I had been taken back to the United States, quarantined for more than ten days in a nice military base hotel, but my God, he had only just left the ship. I wept to see the captain in his uniform, his cap tucked under his arm, still wearing a mask, but still looking optimistic. It's hard to imagine. He did such a good job. Let this be the end of my epidemic diary. Thank you, Captain Alma.

If I ever had to take a cruise again, I wouldn't even think about it.

The isolation was finally over, and I gradually returned to my daily routine. I'm single. I used to be alone. There are negative and terrible times to live in this world, and many people are struggling and suffering. But this time, it wasn't just one person, it was thousands of strangers, all of them supporting me, even sending me gifts to keep me going. These people came together to love, and I was completely ripped open. These changes have restored my faith in people and given me the strength and courage to live more optimistically. I really want to keep this momentum going and make a difference in the world, whether it's through blogging or writing a book. Because there's so much good in this world.

On Feb. 24, people in isolation at the air force base played soccer together to ease anxiety about waiting for the test results. Photo courtesy of the respondents

Finally, I would like to let readers in China know that I am with you. I don't want the Chinese people to think that everyone hates you and blames you for this virus. I know there is some discrimination, and I have denounced it, and others have denounced it. I want you to know that we love you. I know it's not your fault, and you're suffering the same fate. Stay positive. This will pass. Hopefully we can rebuild trust. My heart is with you.

PSST. On Feb. 9, the Diamond Princess announced a full refund for passengers on flights, hotels, ground transportation, shore excursions, tips, and other charges. The tips will be returned to the passengers, but the company will pay the crew what they have already received. All passengers will also get another free trip for the full price. All expenses incurred during the period of isolation are excluded.

The captain of the Diamond Princess, Gennaro Alma, was called the "hero captain" by the Italians for his performance, saying he embodied the spirit of the Italians never give up. Alma became the last person to step off the diamond princess on 1 March, to be awarded the highest national medal by the Italian president, the Italy commander's Medal of honor. As he led 3,710 lives through a dark period of isolation, the 44-year-old often urged: "a diamond is a piece of carbon that does well under pressure. ".
